Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Chop the @potato{1}(chopped into wedges) (no need to peel) into wedges about the size of your index finger. Lay the wedges on a lined #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with @oil{} and sprinkle over a good pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch} and cook on the top shelf of your oven for ~{25-30%mins}, until soft inside and brown on the outside.

Halve, peel and slice the @red onion{2}(halved, peeled and sliced into thin half moons). To make the red onion marmalade, heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a #small saucepan{} on low heat and add your onion with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Add the @balsamic vinegar{3/4}, place a lid on the pan and cook gently, stirring occasionally, ~{20%mins}.

Add the @British beef mince{250} to a #mixing bowl{} and combine with the @harissa spice mix{3/4} and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Form your beef mixture into burger patties (one per person) and make a gentle thumb dent in the centre top of the burgers as this will help them to be level after cooking.

> TIP: Add less harissa if you don't like spice.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and once hot, gently lay in your burgers. Cook for around ~{6-7%mins} on each side turning them only once. If you want to cook your burgers a little more in the middle, you can place them in your oven for a few mins after frying.

> TIP: The burgers are cooked when they are no longer pink in the middle.

While your burgers cook, preheat your #grill{} to high and slice the @brioche buns{2}(sliced in half). Place the buns under your grill for a couple of mins on each side until they are toasted, then remove.

> TIP: Watch out they don't burn!

Lay a burger on the bottom half of each bun. Top with a dollop of @Greek style yoghurt{1/2} and a spoonful of red onion marmalade. Serve your Moroccan beef burgers with some potato wedges and @baby spinach{1/2}(undressed) on the side.

> We left our leaves undressed to balance the richness of the burgers. Enjoy!